    <title>X is allowing people you’ve blocked to see your posts</title>
    <content type="html">  

    &lt;figure&gt;
      &lt;img alt="An image showing the X logo" src="https://cdn.vox-cdn.com/thumbor/s7UC99uME5k8NYTvaaq_S8aGE3M=/1x0:3001x2000/1310x873/cdn.vox-cdn.com/uploads/chorus_image/image/73699665/STK160_X_Twitter_005.0.jpg" /&gt;
        &lt;figcaption&gt;Illustration: The Verge&lt;/figcaption&gt;
    &lt;/figure&gt;

  &lt;p id="NkAXXl"&gt;This weekend, X, the platform formerly known as Twitter, &lt;a href="https://x.com/XEng/status/1852934762144698736"&gt;announced&lt;/a&gt; it’s “starting to launch” a controversial change to how blocking works on its platform. Company owner Elon Musk &lt;a href="https://www.theverge.com/2024/9/23/24252438/x-blocked-users-view-public-posts"&gt;first revealed&lt;/a&gt; the change in September, which will allow people you’ve blocked to continue to see your posts, and, as noted by &lt;a href="https://techcrunch.com/2024/11/03/x-updates-block-feature-letting-blocked-users-see-your-public-posts/"&gt;&lt;em&gt;TechCrunch&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/a&gt;, your following and followers lists. &lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="Rjl8ni"&gt;Musk claimed that stopping people from seeing your public posts “makes no sense,” but due to a post-Musk change that stops logged-out users from scrolling even a public profile, this could make it easier for blocked users to continue harassing someone.&lt;/p&gt;
&lt;p id="uIhagv"&gt;In October, X’s engineering account argued that people who block others could say harmful things about the blocked person who wouldn’t know...&lt;/p&gt;
